@misc{Lewis1981,
   abstract = {JSTOR is a not-for-profit service that helps scholars, researchers, and students discover, use, and build upon a wide range of content in a trusted digital archive. We use information technology and tools to increase productivity and facilitate new forms of scholarship. For more information about JSTOR, please contact support@jstor.org. Abstract. The optimal management of a renewable natural resource under uncertainty is analysed in general terms, and with specific application to the Eastern Pacific yellowfin tuna fishery. Uncertainties about the future size of the resource and about its current market value may exist because of variations in economic and environmental conditions. A Markov Decision Process model is developed to find optimal policies which maximize the discounted stream of expected social returns from resource use. The model is used to answer the following questions. How do optimal deterministic programs for allocating resources compare with programs derived under stochastic conditions? Do different attitudes towards social risk-bearing as regards variations in resource rents have an effect on optimal decision rules? What is the effect of increased uncertainty about resource prices, extraction costs, and resource growth and depletion rates on optimal programs? Exploitation d'une ressource renouvelable en contexte d'incertitude. L'auteur analyse en termes g6neraux la gestion optimale d'une ressource naturelle renouvelable en contexte d'incertitude et en fait une application a la peche du thon dans l'est du Pacifique. Il existe de l'incertitude quant a la dimension de la ressource et quant a la valeur marchande courante a cause des variations dans les parametres de l'economie et de l'environnement. L'auteur utilise un modele de decision de type markovien pour identifier les strategies optimales susceptibles de maximiser le flux escompte de rendements sociaux a partir de l'utilisation de la ressource. Le modele est utilise pour repondre a